{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Human SMIT is a high-affinity myo-inositol transporter, and is expressed in brain, heart, kidney, and lung. Inhibition of myo-inositol uptake, through down-regulation of SMIT, may be a common mechanism of action of mood stabilizers, including lithium, carbamazepine, and valproate [[cite:PUB00093238]]. SMIT is encoded by the SLC5A3 gene, which is a candidate gene for pathogenesis of nervous system dysfunction in Down syndrome (DS) [[cite:PUB00093237]]. The SNP, 21q22 near SLC5A3-MRPS6-KCNE2, has been associated with coronary heart disease, cardiovascular disease, and myocardial infarction [[cite:PUB00093236]]. SMIT may also be involved in the pathogenesis of congenital cataract [[cite:PUB00093235]]. SMIT also plays roles in osteogenesis, bone formation, and bone mineral density determination. SMIT belongs to the solute carrier 5 (SLC5) transporter family [[cite:PUB00093172]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR038377", "name" "Sodium/glucose symporter superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"cdd" {"cd11491" "Na(+)/myo-inositol cotransporter SMIT and related proteins; solute-binding domain"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Sodium/myo-inositol cotransporter SMIT", "short" "SMIT"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 403, "taxa" 1310, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 452, "sets" 0, "proteins" 452, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 390}, "pathways" 3}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR042731", :literature {"PUB00093172" {"URL" nil, "issue" nil, "authors" ["Wright EM" "Loo DD" "Hirayama BA" "Turk E."], "ISO_journal" "Physiology (Bethesda)", "DOI_URL" nil, "medline_journal" "Physiology (Bethesda)", "title" "Surprising versatility of Na+-glucose cotransporters: